  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. Major Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Basel Committee recommendations\n- Increased international cooperation\n\n3. Key Legislative Advancements\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Stricter reporting obligations\n- Expanded definition of predicate offenses\n- More comprehensive compliance frameworks\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Risk-based compliance approaches\n- Machine learning and AI integration\n\n5. Global Regulatory Trends\n- Increased cross-border information sharing\n- Harmonization of international standards\n- Stronger penalties for non-compliance\n- More comprehensive beneficial ownership rules\n\n6. Recent Developments\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Enhanced transparency requirements\n- Sanctions-related compliance\n- Heightened focus on beneficial ownership\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, becoming more sophisticated and technologically integrated to address emerging financial crime risks.",
